40|$|The {{failure of}} the banking system to play its normal role in the {{transmission}} of the monetary stimulus to the economy {{may have contributed to}} the 1990 - 91 recession and the sluggish recovery from it. This paper examines the 1988 Basel Agreement on risk-based capital standards as a possible shock to the credit supply system and finds that banks with larger <b>capital</b> <b>surpluses</b> resulting from the risk-based requirements had faster loan growth between 1987 and 1991 than those with smaller surpluses or which failed the new standards. Newly issued capital in banks with larger <b>capital</b> <b>surpluses</b> was associated with greater loan growth than were the same capital additions in banks with smaller <b>capital</b> <b>surpluses.</b> Copyright 1995 by Ohio State University Press. ...|$|R
