50|$|Lending-limit {{regulations}} {{restrict the}} total amount of loans and credits that a bank may extend to a single borrower. This restriction is usually stated {{as a percentage of the}} bank's capital or assets. For example, a national bank generally must limit its total outstanding loans and credits to any single borrower to no more than 15% of the bank's total <b>capital</b> and <b>surplus.</b> Some state banking regulations also contain similar lending limits applicable to state-chartered banks. Both federal and state laws generally allow for a higher lending limit (up to 25% of <b>capital</b> and <b>surplus</b> for national banks) when the portion of the credit that exceeds the initial lending limit is fully secured.|$|R
